# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1924-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The **1883 New York Gothams season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **San Francisco Giants**.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team replaced the Troy Trojans when the National League awarded its franchise rights to John B.
[src:1924-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team went 46–50, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1924-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The **1884 New York Gothams season** was the second season of that baseball franchise, eventually known as the San Francisco Giants.
[src:1924-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The team finished in fourth place, 22 games behind the pennant-winning Providence Grays.
[src:1924-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The **1886 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fourth season.
[src:1924-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The team had a record of 75–44, finishing third in the National League, 12.5 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1924-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The **1887 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fifth season.
[src:1924-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in fourth place in the National League with a record of 68–55, 10+1⁄2 games behind the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1924-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team amassed 415 stolen bases, the most for any team in the history of the National League.
[src:1924-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The **1888 New York Giants season** was the franchise's sixth season.
[src:1924-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Claiming six future Hall of Famers (Roger Connor, Mickey Welch, Buck Ewing, Tim Keefe, Jim O'Rourke, and John Montgomery Ward), the team won the National League pennant by nine games and defeated the St.
[src:1924-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Keefe led the league in several major statistical categories, including wins, winning percentage, strikeouts, and earned run average.
[src:1924-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The Giants beat the American Association champion St.
[src:1924-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Louis Browns in the World Series, six games to four.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] The **1924 World Series** was the championship series of the 1924 Major League Baseball season.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] The 21st edition of the World Series was a best-of-seven playoff matching the American League (AL) champion Washington Senators against the National League (NL) champion New York Giants, with the Senators defeating the Giants in seven games to win their first championship in club history.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] This was the first major professional sports championship ever won by a Washington, D.C.-based team.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] The Giants became the first team to play in four consecutive World Series, winning in 1921–1922 and losing in 1923–1924, and their veteran manager, John McGraw, made his ninth and final World Series appearance.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] The deciding game of the Series was decided in extra innings, the second such occurrence in MLB history (the first had occurred in 1912).
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Walter Johnson, nearing the end of his playing career at age 36, made his first ever World Series appearance, having completed his first 20-win season since 1919 (with 23 wins).
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] He lost both of his two starts, but was awarded a win in Game 7 with a relief appearance in which he held the Giants scoreless over the final four innings, helping the Senators secure their first championship.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Game 7 is widely considered one of the most dramatic in World Series history.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Johnson struck out 12 Giants batters in Game 1 in a losing cause.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Although that total matched Ed Walsh's number in the 1906 World Series, it came in 12 innings.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Johnson struck out only nine in the first nine innings.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] In Game 7, with the Senators behind 3–1 in the eighth, Bucky Harris hit a routine ground ball to third which hit a pebble and took a bad hop over Giants third baseman Freddie Lindstrom.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Two runners scored on the play, tying the score at three.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Walter Johnson then came in to pitch the ninth, and held the Giants scoreless into extra innings.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] With the score still 3–3, Washington came up in the 12th.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] With one out, and runners on first and second, Earl McNeely hit another grounder at Lindstrom, and again the ball took a bad hop, scoring Muddy Ruel with the Series-winning run.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] This was the first World Series to use the 2–3–2 home game pattern, which would be adapted as the permanent format beginning the following year.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] This was the Senators' only World Series championship victory during the franchise's time in Washington.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] In 1961, the Senators relocated to Minnesota and were rebranded as the Twins, and subsequently won the World Series in 1987 and in 1991.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] This would be the last World Series win for a Washington based team until the Washington Nationals, who were originally the Montreal Expos, won the World Series in 2019, 95 years after the Senators' only triumph.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] In 2020, ESPN named it the third greatest World Series of all-time.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] The Senators tied it at 2–2 with a run in the bottom of the ninth.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] The Giants scored two in the top of the 12th off the Big Train; Washington fought back for a run in the bottom of the inning, but left the tying run on third.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Washington fought back early in the game, scoring 3 runs in 5 innings.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] But the Giants would quickly fight back in the final three frames to tie the game as it went to the bottom of the ninth.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] With Joe Judge representing the potential winning run and 1 out, Roger Peckinpaugh hit a double to win the game and tie the series.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Ossie Bluege, the only man reliever Claude Jonnard faced, drew a bases-loaded walk to make it 6-4.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Mule Watson then came in to nail down the last two outs.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Rosy Ryan's fourth-inning home run is to date the only World Series home run by a relief pitcher and the only postseason home run by a relief pitcher until Travis Wood in 2016.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Goose Goslin had a big game for the Senators, with three singles and a home run to go 4-for-4 and drive in four runs.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Johnson again pitched a complete game but the Giants recorded 13 hits off him, taking a 3–2 lead in the Series.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Bentley broke a 1–1 tie in the fifth with a two-run home run, the second homer by a New York pitcher in the Series after Rosy Ryan's in Game 3.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Both Washington runs scored on a single in the fifth inning by manager Bucky Harris.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Tom Zachary won his second game of the series, deadlocking the series at three games each.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] The unheralded Curly Ogden was given the Game 7 start for Washington – it was his only World Series appearance.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] He struck out a batter and walked one, and then was pulled for George Mogridge.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] It was later revealed that manager Bucky Harris started righthander Ogden so that the Giants would be locked into their "righthanded" lineup, before he switched to the lefthander Mogridge.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] With the Senators trailing 3–1 in the eighth inning with bases loaded and two outs, Bucky Harris hit a "bad hop" ground ball to third, that reportedly struck a pebble, which Freddie Lindstrom failed to catch (no error was charged).
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] As a result, two runs scored for a 3–3 tie.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] In the ninth inning, Walter Johnson would step up as pitcher and pitch four scoreless innings.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] In the bottom of the 12th inning, Giants catcher Hank Gowdy stepped on his own discarded mask while trying to catch a Muddy Ruel foul pop-up, and dropped the ball for an error.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Given a second chance in the at-bat, Ruel doubled.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Johnson reached first on another error, and with Ruel on second and Johnson on first, Earl McNeely hit a "bad hop" ground ball to Lindstrom that was almost identical to Harris' eighth inning hit.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] Lindstrom again failed to catch the ball (reportedly hitting the same pebble that was struck four innings earlier) as it bounced over him into left field, and Ruel scored the series-winning run.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] The game holds the record as the longest Game 7 (by innings) in MLB postseason history.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] It was also the first World Series Game 7 to be decided in extra innings (although the 1912 series ended with a ten-inning Game 8), and the last until 1991.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] In 2014, on the Series' 90th anniversary, the Library of Congress acquired a newsreel of highlight footage from Game 7, including McNeely's Series-winning base hit.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] CNN subsequently released this footage on its website.
[src:1924-world-series/1924-world-series] The next time a Washington team won the World Series would come 95 years later in 2019, when the Washington Nationals did so against the Houston Astros.
[src:1924-world-series/giants-season] The **1885 New York Giants season** was the franchise's third season.
[src:1924-world-series/giants-season] The team finished in second place, 2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
